Brain Tumor Classification using GoogLeNet

This project implements a deep learning model for classifying brain MRI images into multiple tumor categories using a pretrained GoogLeNet (Inception) architecture in PyTorch. The model is trained on a structured dataset with class-wise image folders and incorporates data augmentation techniques such as random cropping, flipping, and rotation to improve generalization. A stratified splitting strategy is used to create balanced training, validation, and test sets, ensuring reliable performance evaluation.
The model achieves strong performance, with validation accuracy around 90% and test accuracy around 86%, depending on dataset size and variability. The pipeline is designed to be modular and extensible, allowing easy experimentation with different architectures, hyperparameters, and augmentation strategies. Additionally, the project can be extended with Grad-CAM visualizations to interpret model predictions and highlight important regions in MRI images.
This project is built using Python, PyTorch, torchvision, and scikit-learn. To run the project, clone the repository, install the required dependencies, update the dataset path, and execute the training script. Future improvements include experimenting with more advanced models such as ResNet or Vision Transformers, increasing dataset size, and further optimizing training and evaluation strategies.
